  <h2>The manifestation team determined that my child's behavior was:</h2>
  <p>not a manifestation of his or her  disability and the behavior involved <span class="def" id="drugs">drugs or alcohol*</span><strong>.</strong> </p>
</div>
  <h2>Response: </h2>
<p>The  school district may suspend or expel your child just as it would a student  without a disability. However, the district must provide alternative  educational services to the extent a suspension or expulsion exceeds five  consecutive school days.<sup class="statute">1</sup></p>
<p>If  the behavior involved a firearm, a school board must expel your child for a  period of at least one year, although the school board may modify this one-year  expulsion requirement on a case-by-case basis.<sup class="statute">2</sup></p>
<p class="tip">TIP: If the discipline is  an expulsion, the school must offer your child an appropriate <span class="def" id="alternate-educational-setting">alternative  educational placement*</span> before beginning expulsion proceedings.<sup class="statute">3</sup> You may choose to accept the alternative placement instead of going forward  with the expulsion proceedings. It is always a good idea to visit the proposed  placement before making a decision.</p>
